WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:04.200
NICK FARMER: So I'd like
to welcome everybody here

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:06.430
to another Talk at Google.

00:00:06.430 --> 00:00:10.416
With us today, we have
Naren Shankar, Mark Fergus,

00:00:10.416 --> 00:00:16.294
two of the show runners
for Syfy's "The Expanse."

00:00:16.294 --> 00:00:17.252
NAREN SHANKAR: Hello.

00:00:17.252 --> 00:00:18.210
MARK FERGUS: Thank you.

00:00:18.210 --> 00:00:20.480
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:22.534 --> 00:00:24.700
NICK FARMER: So I'd just
like to jump in and ask you

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:27.960
guys, what do you think
makes "The Expanse"

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.680
different from other
science fiction shows?

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:35.330
NAREN SHANKAR: Hmm,
well, the low quality

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:38.924
of the writing on which
is was based, obviously.

00:00:38.924 --> 00:00:43.640
No, I think everybody had the
same reaction to the material

00:00:43.640 --> 00:00:44.450
when we read it.

00:00:44.450 --> 00:00:48.020
It's a different look at space.

00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:49.880
It is about the small people.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:52.370
It's not about the
admirals, and the people

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:54.250
who are in charge of starships.

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:58.460
It is a more intimate, it's
a more boots on the ground

00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:00.760
version of it.

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:02.266
You should--

00:01:02.266 --> 00:01:03.807
MARK FERGUS: Yeah,
I think, again, we

00:01:03.807 --> 00:01:07.120
had all responded to the
same things in the novels,

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:10.260
but we felt like Syfy
the genre had always

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:14.440
skipped over the first couple
of years of colonization.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:19.470
What we consider the real
interesting story is how did we

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:20.900
claw our way off the planet?

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:25.390
How do did get out to the
Moon, Mars, the solar system,

00:01:25.390 --> 00:01:27.620
bringing all our
daemons with us,

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:29.680
all our cultural
baggage, everything,

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:34.460
and show how we forge the way
to "Star Trek" and "Galactica"

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:35.950
and all these other
classic shows,

00:01:35.950 --> 00:01:41.080
where technology was sorted out,
and aliens had been contacted,

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:43.180
and we were dealing with them.

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:46.410
The first couple of centuries,
we kept thinking of it

00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:48.920
as the railroads coming
to America's story, where

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:51.770
the landscape changed
because of technology,

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:53.700
and let's just
bring that to space.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:55.510
That was the
fascinating story to us,

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:57.819
and nobody had told it
particularly well until we read

00:01:57.819 --> 00:02:00.360
"The Expanse" books, and we were
like, this is the show we've

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:02.704
always wanted to see.

00:02:02.704 --> 00:02:04.210
Let's go make that
show, as opposed

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:08.900
to thousands of other properties
that were really cool too,

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:11.880
but this is a story that
we've been dying to see.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.160
NAREN SHANKAR: It was
also unique in that space

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:16.780
was a character in the show.

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:19.360
All of the things that
people ignore usually,

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:23.110
things like gravity,
and oxygen, and air,

00:02:23.110 --> 00:02:26.820
and the things that make
space such an inhospitable

00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.390
environment for
human life, those

00:02:29.390 --> 00:02:34.330
are whisked away in most
shows, with transporter beams

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:38.860
and artificial gravity
plating, and the fact that you

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:41.440
can have instantaneous
communication anywhere

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.470
across the galaxy.

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:45.740
This show was different.

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:49.080
It allowed us to have space
become a real character

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:52.660
dramatically in the series,
and we tried to exploit that.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:55.500
MARK FERGUS: And just
following up on that,

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:59.210
space battle becomes
hard and difficult,

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:01.610
the way old ship battle used
to be, submarine battle.

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:02.300
It was slow.

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:03.270
It was anticipatory.

00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:06.650
It was like playing chess rather
than vast and instantaneous

00:03:06.650 --> 00:03:10.210
distances, are vast
like crossing an ocean.

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:13.360
Communication takes--
you call someone on Mars,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.170
and it takes a half
hour to get a response.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:20.535
And so we're back to pre-cell
phone kind of communication,

00:03:20.535 --> 00:03:22.120
not where battles--
and things have

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:26.360
to happen where by the
time you say something

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:30.040
to the field of a battle,
by the time it reaches you

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:32.030
and you get a message
back, the battle's over.

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:34.113
So you have to think in
an entirely different way.

00:03:34.113 --> 00:03:36.370
And yes, space is a character.

00:03:36.370 --> 00:03:37.850
It's vast.

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:38.410
It's huge.

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:40.326
The speed of light is
only the speed of light.

00:03:40.326 --> 00:03:43.025
Only, there's limitations that
we put back on storytelling

00:03:43.025 --> 00:03:44.650
that most sci-fi
says, oh, don't worry.

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:46.480
Technology solved all that.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:47.744
The engine is dead.

00:03:47.744 --> 00:03:48.910
Everyone's still in gravity?

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:50.360
Don't ask why?

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:51.659
It's just part of the deal.

00:03:51.659 --> 00:03:52.450
And we're like, no.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:55.014
If you stop moving, and
your thrust is gone,

00:03:55.014 --> 00:03:56.430
you're going to
start floating up.

00:03:56.430 --> 00:03:58.340
And that becomes a
really cool thing

00:03:58.340 --> 00:04:00.380
that we weave into the
story that we get to use,

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:02.826
instead of just
brushing over it.

00:04:02.826 --> 00:04:04.700
And the books are full
of that kind of thing.

00:04:04.700 --> 00:04:06.930
I think that's what
we responded to.

00:04:06.930 --> 00:04:10.100
That's a space story
we haven't seen before.

00:04:10.100 --> 00:04:13.170
NICK FARMER: And so what's it
from a creative perspective

00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:16.209
that you're writing
these things?

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:20.300
What are the challenges
that you've come up with?

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:22.180
NAREN SHANKAR: So many.

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:23.550
It's a very ambitious show.

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:29.400
I mean, first of all, all
these things like zero gravity,

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:32.350
they're traditionally
not often done,

00:04:32.350 --> 00:04:36.030
and the books are full of them.

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:38.140
It's got a very big scope.

00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:41.340
It's got a lot of
different characters.

00:04:41.340 --> 00:04:45.190
The show was originally sold
really as "Game of Thrones"

00:04:45.190 --> 00:04:49.307
in space, and it has
that quality to it.

00:04:49.307 --> 00:04:51.640
And that's certainly something
that we've tried to play,

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:54.310
but it means you've got to
build a lot of big sets.

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:56.000
You've got to create
these environments.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:57.333
You've got to build space ships.

00:04:57.333 --> 00:05:00.650
You've got a tremendous
amount of visual effects work.

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:05.846
It is as complex a show as
I've ever been involved in.

00:05:05.846 --> 00:05:08.220
MARK FERGUS: And then we had
talked about it earlier too.

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:09.790
There's things that
are on the page,

00:05:09.790 --> 00:05:15.100
like Belters are tall and
light because reduced gravity

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:18.580
changes the cartilage,
changes the bone structure,

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:21.220
changes the physicality,
which we love,

00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:22.970
because it's
essentially technology

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:24.550
leads to us going
out into space.

00:05:24.550 --> 00:05:27.180
And as a result of that,
a new race of humans

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:29.234
is created by environment.

00:05:29.234 --> 00:05:31.650
They're still human, and yet
they're completely different.

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:33.520
They can never go
back to full G planets

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:36.184
and live, because their
bodies have grown up.

00:05:36.184 --> 00:05:37.600
Production-wise,
how are you going

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:39.880
to get hundreds,
thousands of seven

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:43.012
foot tall, very skinny
great actors as well?

00:05:43.012 --> 00:05:44.970
NAREN SHANKAR: The answer,
of course, is money.

00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:47.185
MARK FERGUS: Right.

00:05:47.185 --> 00:05:50.630
So in the absence
of that, we decided

00:05:50.630 --> 00:05:56.020
to create the full spectrum of--
this was an adaptation problem.

00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:59.290
On the page it's easy
to say everybody looks

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.205
like this on the screen.

00:06:01.205 --> 00:06:02.580
Unless we're an
animated film, we

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:05.170
have to do this in a smart way.

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:09.090
So it ended up becoming a
great opportunity to say,

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:11.800
yes, there are extreme
belters with the full range

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:13.590
of physicality.

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.740
In essence, the poorer you
were, the more difficult

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:18.970
your economic upbringing,
you're on zero G ships,

00:06:18.970 --> 00:06:20.200
you're way out in the system.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:23.040
The more difficult your
economic situation is,

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:24.850
the more Belter you
would be, because you'd

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:26.410
be in harder conditions.

00:06:26.410 --> 00:06:29.934
And we did the full spectrum,
so you could have race traitors.

00:06:29.934 --> 00:06:31.600
You could have people
hiding, pretending

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:33.725
they're an Earther, when
they're actually a Belter.

00:06:33.725 --> 00:06:36.452
You can have extreme Belters,
who are looked down on.

00:06:36.452 --> 00:06:39.165
You have Earthers
slumming it, wanting

00:06:39.165 --> 00:06:40.290
to pretend they're Belters.

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:41.990
You have a whole
range of stuff now.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:43.620
We can put that in
the story as opposed

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:47.192
to that monolithic kind
of-- Ty had always called it

00:06:47.192 --> 00:06:49.560
the thing of a lot of sci-fi.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:51.077
A race of people looks the same.

00:06:51.077 --> 00:06:51.910
They speak the same.

00:06:51.910 --> 00:06:55.155
They have the same
attitude about everything.

00:06:55.155 --> 00:06:59.505
They're a race, and that
wouldn't-- I feel that for this

00:06:59.505 --> 00:07:01.630
show, that would have gotten
boring really quickly.

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:03.255
So I'm glad that we
had the constraint,

00:07:03.255 --> 00:07:08.330
because it came to, I think,
a cooler solution, definitely.

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:11.230
NICK FARMER: So for
those who may not know,

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:13.760
Ty Franck and Daniel
Abraham, the authors

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.040
who combine to make the
pen name James SA Corey,

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.594
have an unprecedented
level of participation

00:07:21.594 --> 00:07:22.760
in the creation of the show.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:26.570
And what's that like for you,
to work with the authors,

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:31.090
to have them with
you at all times?

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:33.380
NAREN SHANKAR: When I was
brought onto the show,

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:36.460
and Mark and his writing
partner Hawk Ostby,

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:39.700
they wrote the pilot, and
I was brought in later,

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:42.710
after it was sold to Syfy.

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:48.290
And I was told, you start
the show, and here we go.

00:07:48.290 --> 00:07:49.540
I'm going to go do the series.

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:51.680
And by the way, the two
writers who wrote the book

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:52.890
are going to be in the room.

00:07:52.890 --> 00:07:56.130
And I was, are you sure
that's a really good idea?

00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:59.874
Because usually authors can
be very precious with what

00:07:59.874 --> 00:08:00.540
they've written.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:02.080
They don't want to
change anything.

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:08.180
But very quickly we
found that Ty and Daniel

00:08:08.180 --> 00:08:13.350
were incredibly open to
truly adapting the material

00:08:13.350 --> 00:08:14.280
to a different medium.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:17.370
It's like things that they
do in the book would not

00:08:17.370 --> 00:08:20.060
have lent themselves
to the story the way

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:24.360
we're portraying it
dramatically on television.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:25.900
The first book is
two characters.

00:08:25.900 --> 00:08:27.360
It's told from two perspectives.

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:29.980
The chapters alternate
between them.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.250
We had to bring in other
elements to the show,

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:35.530
and so they were
incredibly open to it,

00:08:35.530 --> 00:08:38.214
and we actually started
pulling in material

00:08:38.214 --> 00:08:39.130
that they had written.

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:41.450
They had written novellas
to support the material,

00:08:41.450 --> 00:08:45.240
and we started bringing those
in, characters from books

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:47.320
further along in the series.

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:53.180
And what it enabled us to do
was truly adapt the material.

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:55.590
It's a slightly
different thing, but it's

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:58.290
remained incredibly true
to the source material

00:08:58.290 --> 00:08:59.720
all along the way.

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:03.350
And with Ty and Daniel there,
we don't break anything.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:06.470
There have been times when we'll
go, oh, what if we do this,

00:09:06.470 --> 00:09:09.900
and they're like, well, you're
going to totally ruin book 5.

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:11.825
And we're like, OK, we
won't do that, then.

00:09:11.825 --> 00:09:13.783
And so we figure out a
different way around it.

00:09:13.783 --> 00:09:18.720
And also at times, we'll
be looking for, well, gee,

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.560
can we do something in this
episode that illuminates

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:22.660
a part of Belter culture?

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:24.160
It's like, if only
we had something,

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:26.780
and Ty will say, well, what if
you did this thing that I've

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:28.150
got three books down the line?

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:29.410
We're like, that's perfect.

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:30.160
Let's put that in.

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.980
And so they allow us
to stay on target.

00:09:33.980 --> 00:09:38.790
They exploit the scope of the
world that they've created,

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:42.876
and we're just the
beneficiaries of that.

00:09:42.876 --> 00:09:44.650
MARK FERGUS: Yeah.

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:46.690
NICK FARMER: Just a
light hearted question.

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:51.150
If you were to pick a
faction for yourselves,

00:09:51.150 --> 00:09:56.460
would you be Earthers,
Martians, or Belters?

00:09:56.460 --> 00:10:00.280
MARK FERGUS: I think the Belters
are really what the books are

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:03.430
about, ultimately.

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:05.710
I feel like definitely,
because that's

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:07.710
where all the drama is
going on, and that's

00:10:07.710 --> 00:10:11.382
where all of the
passion in the story is.

00:10:11.382 --> 00:10:14.970
They're these scattered
tribes of people flung out

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:17.340
of into the solar system,
trying to figure out

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:21.710
some identity for themselves,
to collect together,

00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:26.260
to stay as tribes, to survive
out there in a new environment.

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:28.220
You've got the
empires, fighting over

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:31.450
who's going to be the top dog,
and of course, the Belters

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:34.360
are at the shit end
of that, usually.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:38.450
The people who built the
apparatus for the empires

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:40.720
to exist out in the
solar system then become

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.820
exiles out in space,
and they're forgotten.

00:10:42.820 --> 00:10:46.570
And that's where all the
really cool grist is,

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:47.670
I think, in this story.

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:49.485
And I think they're
also the coolest

00:10:49.485 --> 00:10:51.360
and the most interesting
people in the story.

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:56.300
The Earth is the old the
new empire, old, empire

00:10:56.300 --> 00:10:59.540
thing, which I think
human behavior seems

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:01.110
to always go that way, anyway.

00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:03.980
So one of the things we
loved about the stories too,

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:07.360
it's just the endless
cycle of rising and falling

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:10.690
and building, and
oppressed class, empire,

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:13.410
leading to crusty old empire
that falls into the sea.

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:15.750
The other one becomes
the crusty old--

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:20.040
it's just the way we're wired,
and the story in a larger

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:21.402
sense, what happens?

00:11:21.402 --> 00:11:22.860
Is there any way
out of that cycle?

00:11:22.860 --> 00:11:26.610
Is there any technological
or spiritual way

00:11:26.610 --> 00:11:29.040
out of that endless cycle?

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:33.060
So to make a short answer to
the question, it's Belters.

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:36.280
I think I wandered from
the-- which I will do.

00:11:36.280 --> 00:11:38.649
Just got to go, get
back, get back, get back.

00:11:38.649 --> 00:11:40.440
NAREN SHANKAR: As a
humorless technologist,

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:43.810
I'd probably be a Martian.

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:46.320
I've definitely
noticed from the fans

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:48.360
that even though the
Martians haven't appeared

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:51.010
so much in season
one, a lot of people

00:11:51.010 --> 00:11:54.420
really like the idea of
having the sleek ships

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:55.670
and the big guns.

00:11:55.670 --> 00:11:56.660
MARK FERGUS: They
got the cool stuff.

00:11:56.660 --> 00:11:57.618
NAREN SHANKAR: They do.

00:11:57.618 --> 00:11:58.770
They have the cool stuff.

00:11:58.770 --> 00:12:00.020
MARK FERGUS: Belters rocks.

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:01.810
NICK FARMER: Yeah,
well, that works too

00:12:01.810 --> 00:12:03.060
under the right circumstances.

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:04.143
MARK FERGUS: That's right.

00:12:04.143 --> 00:12:05.610
And cargo containers
with engines.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:06.960
NAREN SHANKAR: Exactly.

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:09.410
Spoiler alert.

00:12:09.410 --> 00:12:13.520
NICK FARMER: I'm a little
partial to the Belters myself.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:15.270
MARK FERGUS: Understandably.

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:15.540
You made the language.

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:16.790
NICK FARMER: Yeah, I mean, it's
because I'm over six feet tall.

00:12:16.790 --> 00:12:18.904
MARK FERGUS: You made
the language too.

00:12:18.904 --> 00:12:21.240
That's true.

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:28.500
NICK FARMER: So you have a PhD
in physics and engineering.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:30.250
Can you tell us a
little about your story,

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:33.660
going from that to Hollywood?

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:35.700
NAREN SHANKAR: I had
an odd trajectory.

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:40.870
I started as a humanities
student in medieval studies.

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:42.230
NICK FARMER: Gasp in Google.

00:12:42.230 --> 00:12:42.990
NAREN SHANKAR: Yeah, I know.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:44.880
Medieval studies,
French literature, but I

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:48.056
had always loved
science and mathematics.

00:12:48.056 --> 00:12:49.430
And I think in my
sophomore year,

00:12:49.430 --> 00:12:52.130
I realized that the
chance of actually getting

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:54.010
a job with the degrees
that I was looking at

00:12:54.010 --> 00:12:55.080
were probably quite slim.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.480
So I transferred
into engineering.

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:01.110
And it's also cultural.

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:03.771
First generation Indian is like
doctor, lawyer, businessman,

00:13:03.771 --> 00:13:04.270
engineer.

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.270
That's what you've got to do.

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:10.070
And so I transferred into
engineering, and I stayed.

00:13:10.070 --> 00:13:11.990
And I stayed all the
way through to my PhD.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:14.430
But as I was finishing
my dissertation,

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:19.130
I started-- I mean, the things
that I loved were history,

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:21.980
and so I started taking
more and more courses

00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:23.860
in the liberal arts college.

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:25.930
And I think it just
got to the point

00:13:25.930 --> 00:13:29.580
where I had that moment
where I was coming out.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:31.910
I was taking a
course in the history

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:34.190
of American foreign
policy taught

00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:36.230
by this amazing
professor at Cornell.

00:13:36.230 --> 00:13:39.940
And I came out of this terrific
lecture about Aaron Burr,

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:41.640
and I was walking
back to my lab.

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:43.727
And I could see it down
at the end of the street,

00:13:43.727 --> 00:13:44.810
and I was like, oh my god.

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:47.210
I can't do this anymore.

00:13:47.210 --> 00:13:49.070
And it was not I didn't
love engineering.

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:49.685
I did it.

00:13:49.685 --> 00:13:54.570
It was I felt myself becoming
more and more of a specialist

00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:56.900
in a smaller and smaller
corner of the universe,

00:13:56.900 --> 00:13:58.430
and that just wasn't
my personality.

00:13:58.430 --> 00:14:01.730
And I finished the dissertation,
and I told my parents

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:07.370
that I was going to go to
Los Angeles and be a writer.

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:09.680
And to their credit, my
parents were adorable.

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:11.260
They were very supportive.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:13.130
And I started
college really young,

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:16.160
and so they figured I had
a couple years to burn.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:20.180
And I drove, and I'd come to
my senses and get a real job.

00:14:20.180 --> 00:14:23.069
But as I was driving
away 10 years later,

00:14:23.069 --> 00:14:25.360
my mother told me, as soon
as my car went out of sight,

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:27.820
she burst into tears.

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:29.080
But it worked out OK.

00:14:29.080 --> 00:14:29.905
It worked out OK.

00:14:29.905 --> 00:14:32.010
That's the long story.

00:14:32.010 --> 00:14:36.010
NICK FARMER: I've
heard a story that tied

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:39.690
into why you were graduating
from college young,

00:14:39.690 --> 00:14:42.877
a you were little bit ahead,
and you had a briefcase.

00:14:42.877 --> 00:14:46.010
NAREN SHANKAR: God damn it, Ty.

00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:46.540
Yes.

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:48.160
Yes, I own this story.

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:51.100
When I was in like sixth
grade, my parents, who

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:52.750
were immigrants,
they thought it would

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:56.600
be awesome to give their son
a briefcase to take to school.

00:14:56.600 --> 00:14:59.670
And like a good son,
I took it to school

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:01.290
for like the next four years.

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:06.522
And let me tell you, that was
a chick magnet, a briefcase.

00:15:06.522 --> 00:15:08.605
No, I had a good friend,
who actually every day we

00:15:08.605 --> 00:15:10.510
would come back from school,
he would kick the shit out

00:15:10.510 --> 00:15:11.360
of the briefcase.

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:14.352
And in my sophomore year of
high school, it exploded.

00:15:14.352 --> 00:15:16.060
Almost everything went
all over the snow,

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:17.997
and I was just done
with the briefcase.

00:15:17.997 --> 00:15:19.330
NICK FARMER: No more briefcases?

00:15:19.330 --> 00:15:20.746
NAREN SHANKAR: No
more briefcases.

00:15:23.466 --> 00:15:25.716
MARK FERGUS: That's [INAUDIBLE]
I'm just picturing it.

00:15:25.716 --> 00:15:26.924
NAREN SHANKAR: It was so sad.

00:15:29.352 --> 00:15:30.810
NICK FARMER: Well,
I mean, I wonder

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:32.476
if any of those people
who tormented you

00:15:32.476 --> 00:15:34.405
are watching your shows.

00:15:34.405 --> 00:15:36.830
I mean, you probably
have some fans who

00:15:36.830 --> 00:15:38.560
don't even make the connection.

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:41.060
NAREN SHANKAR: Yeah,
screw those guys.

00:15:41.060 --> 00:15:42.880
I hope they are.

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:45.550
NICK FARMER: So I'd like
to give everybody time

00:15:45.550 --> 00:15:47.060
to think about their questions.

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:49.140
We're setting up
a mic over here.

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:53.000
And make sure that
when you line up

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:59.230
that you are lined
up behind each other.

00:15:59.230 --> 00:16:00.730
I'm a linguist,
and I can't talk.

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:02.837
NAREN SHANKAR: I
was going to say.

00:16:02.837 --> 00:16:03.670
NICK FARMER: I know.

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:06.110
Well, this is why you guys
had to hire a voice coach,

00:16:06.110 --> 00:16:07.940
and you couldn't just have
me work with the actors.

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:09.814
I mean, I would go in
there, and I would just

00:16:09.814 --> 00:16:11.544
mess up my own language.

00:16:11.544 --> 00:16:12.710
NAREN SHANKAR: That was fun.

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:14.543
Mark did a lot of that
with the voice acting

00:16:14.543 --> 00:16:16.880
and the coaching of the Belters.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:20.350
MARK FERGUS: Yeah, well, I
worked for an entire year

00:16:20.350 --> 00:16:24.150
on a show, where Nick
created an entire language

00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:25.000
for the Belters.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.332
And we probably would have
worked countless hours.

00:16:28.332 --> 00:16:31.021
I literally met him for the
first time two days ago,

00:16:31.021 --> 00:16:32.520
and spoke to him
for the first time,

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:35.500
even though we did
a show together.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.265
But yeah, it would be
lines going to Nick.

00:16:38.265 --> 00:16:40.890
He would create the language,
then it would come back.

00:16:40.890 --> 00:16:44.910
We would bring them to our
dialect coach, essentially.

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:49.660
He would teach people how
to act and say and inflect

00:16:49.660 --> 00:16:53.920
in a completely created language
with a very specific accent.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:56.750
And some actors dove into that.

00:16:56.750 --> 00:17:00.570
Other actors were terrified
to not only learn your lines

00:17:00.570 --> 00:17:03.320
and feel it, and swim in
it, and get all the subtext,

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:05.290
but also learn a new
language and a new accent

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:07.430
now, and be ready tomorrow.

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:09.150
It was a little frightening.

00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:11.316
NAREN SHANKAR: It was a
great thing in the show too.

00:17:11.316 --> 00:17:12.910
Because one of the
things in the book

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:16.220
was that humanity had
gone out into the Belt.

00:17:16.220 --> 00:17:21.099
It wasn't just white Americans
going out into space.

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:23.930
It was the Russians, the
Chinese, the Indians.

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:26.720
And so the Belt was
this polyglot mix

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:29.170
of different cultures
and language styles

00:17:29.170 --> 00:17:30.610
and little pieces of them.

00:17:30.610 --> 00:17:34.080
And the Martians had different
strains in their language

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:34.900
as well.

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:37.260
And it's just been a
really interesting thing,

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:40.230
because when you start
feeling those little threads,

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:41.730
you start feeling
those little bits

00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:44.324
and pieces of human culture
in this different place,

00:17:44.324 --> 00:17:46.740
it was just a unique thing in
the show that I really like.

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:47.820
I really loved that.

00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:48.861
MARK FERGUS: It was cool.

00:17:48.861 --> 00:17:50.850
I don't know who-- was
it Ty's or your analogy

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:54.920
of the Mediterranean
fishing village.

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:58.330
Space is just considered
all these different factions

00:17:58.330 --> 00:18:02.500
coming to work in space, and
coming, going, transporting.

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:04.580
And what happens to
language and culture

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:07.425
over hundreds of years in that
kind of transitory environment?

00:18:07.425 --> 00:18:10.060
And that's where the
language came from.

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:12.380
And it was great,
because we could

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:13.946
do anything we wanted
with it, but we

00:18:13.946 --> 00:18:15.570
wanted to stick to
structure and rules,

00:18:15.570 --> 00:18:17.550
so it didn't feel like bull.

00:18:17.550 --> 00:18:20.655
It felt like a real language
with a history and a structure.

00:18:20.655 --> 00:18:22.180
NAREN SHANKAR:
Even the gestures.

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:23.490
MARK FERGUS: Yeah.

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:25.730
NAREN SHANKAR: It's described
as a gestural language,

00:18:25.730 --> 00:18:29.690
and Ty and Daniel are saying
that it was derived from people

00:18:29.690 --> 00:18:32.520
in space suits who spoke
different languages not being

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:34.170
able to talk to one another.

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:39.750
So they adopted some very broad
signaling, gestural signaling,

00:18:39.750 --> 00:18:42.170
with their hands so they could
look at each other in space

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:43.190
and understand it.

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:46.630
And over time, that
concept had boiled

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:50.430
down into a very expressive
hand gestures along with Belter.

00:18:50.430 --> 00:18:52.090
And so that was
part of it as well,

00:18:52.090 --> 00:18:55.200
and it's lovely when you
can pull details like that

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:57.290
into a show, because it
just grounds the world.

00:18:57.290 --> 00:18:59.890
It makes it all feel very real.

00:18:59.890 --> 00:19:03.204
MARK FERGUS: So
thank you for that.

00:19:03.204 --> 00:19:05.120
AUDIENCE: So you touched
on this a little bit,

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:07.980
talking about the
Belters height and stuff

00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:10.130
and having to change a
little bit from the books.

00:19:10.130 --> 00:19:13.470
But I had a question about
doing practical effects

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:16.490
for the low gravity
areas, like Ceres.

00:19:16.490 --> 00:19:19.180
Because you have the drones
flying around in the shots.

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:21.290
And I haven't finished
the show, so maybe there's

00:19:21.290 --> 00:19:24.132
something like this in a later
episode, but showing somebody.

00:19:24.132 --> 00:19:25.840
Picking up something
impractically heavy,

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:28.040
or having an
occasional object not

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:30.800
fall as fast as
you would expect,

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:32.290
or anything like
that, because it's

00:19:32.290 --> 00:19:33.706
a little offputting
for them to be

00:19:33.706 --> 00:19:36.430
talking about how it's
gravity, and then everything's

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:37.240
like heavy.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:39.170
MARK FERGUS: Yeah,
we had to choose.

00:19:39.170 --> 00:19:42.800
I think we had to create-- We
had talked about this earlier,

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:44.190
as well.

00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:47.890
Ceres is a third G
environment, and it

00:19:47.890 --> 00:19:50.780
would affect lots of
areas of behavior,

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:53.660
how Earthers would walk and
be too ahead of themselves.

00:19:53.660 --> 00:19:55.840
They'd be jumping all the
time, objects falling.

00:19:55.840 --> 00:19:58.570
I think what we tried
to do is tell the story,

00:19:58.570 --> 00:20:01.840
make sure that people understood
this is not normal gravity.

00:20:01.840 --> 00:20:04.210
But then don't let it get
in the way of every scene.

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:06.240
Otherwise, you just
can't tell the story.

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:08.406
And so we put things like
a bird flapping its wings.

00:20:08.406 --> 00:20:10.222
AUDIENCE: The budget, I realize
you can't put everybody on a--

00:20:10.222 --> 00:20:10.478
NAREN SHANKAR: I'm sorry.

00:20:10.478 --> 00:20:10.676
What was that?

00:20:10.676 --> 00:20:11.440
AUDIENCE: I was going
to say, I realize

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:13.398
you don't have the budget
to film every episode

00:20:13.398 --> 00:20:15.110
on the vomit comet.

00:20:15.110 --> 00:20:18.026
MARK FERGUS: No, even
so, it would be--

00:20:18.026 --> 00:20:19.650
NAREN SHANKAR: When
we talked about it,

00:20:19.650 --> 00:20:23.670
it was ultimately those things
would get normalized out

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:27.740
very quickly, and Ceres would
be like, even though everything

00:20:27.740 --> 00:20:30.210
was maybe not as heavy
as a similar object would

00:20:30.210 --> 00:20:32.760
be on Earth, relative
to Ceres, everything

00:20:32.760 --> 00:20:33.950
would be accounted for.

00:20:33.950 --> 00:20:38.170
So the number of times that you
can actually show differences

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:40.600
were actually fairly small,
because it's how do you

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:42.200
show weight on television?

00:20:42.200 --> 00:20:43.510
It's very tough.

00:20:43.510 --> 00:20:45.470
So what we did is we
picked a couple of things.

00:20:45.470 --> 00:20:48.530
Coriolis is one of them,
in that in different parts

00:20:48.530 --> 00:20:51.660
of the station, if you pour
a fluid, the deflection

00:20:51.660 --> 00:20:54.140
of the fluid relative to
where you were in the station

00:20:54.140 --> 00:20:56.090
and the spin gravity
causes it to deflect.

00:20:56.090 --> 00:20:59.850
So you see that when Miller is
pouring from his scotch bottle.

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:04.020
Instead of going like this, it
goes like that into the glass.

00:21:04.020 --> 00:21:09.470
When you see a bird, the sparrow
that he flips a little peanut

00:21:09.470 --> 00:21:13.260
to or whatever on his
balcony, that bird

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:19.104
was meticulously animated so
that the beating of the wings

00:21:19.104 --> 00:21:21.270
is a little bit different
than it would be on Earth.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:25.010
So the smaller
moments where you can

00:21:25.010 --> 00:21:29.360
establish a different gravity
situation were more effective.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:31.364
We tried, and one thing
we completely failed

00:21:31.364 --> 00:21:32.780
at doing-- there
are two things we

00:21:32.780 --> 00:21:35.150
failed at doing
in the pilot, was

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:37.730
a bicycle stunt-- oh my god.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.990
What a nightmare--
In the pilot to try

00:21:40.990 --> 00:21:44.030
to show a reduced gravity flip.

00:21:44.030 --> 00:21:45.930
It was misconceived.

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:47.160
The director hated it.

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:48.210
We made him shoot it.

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:51.230
We spent half a
fucking day-- sorry.

00:21:51.230 --> 00:21:51.730
And a day--

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:53.105
MARK FERGUS: No,
that's worth it.

00:21:53.105 --> 00:21:55.450
NAREN SHANKAR: And we cut it
out of the pilot entirely.

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:56.490
MARK FERGUS: It
just didn't work.

00:21:56.490 --> 00:21:57.340
NAREN SHANKAR:
And the other one,

00:21:57.340 --> 00:21:59.270
we had one scene that we
could never make work,

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:00.853
because we all thought
it was comical.

00:22:00.853 --> 00:22:03.880
It was Miller has an
Earth partner who's come

00:22:03.880 --> 00:22:05.430
to Ceres for the first time.

00:22:05.430 --> 00:22:07.740
And we thought it would
be interesting if there's

00:22:07.740 --> 00:22:09.700
a chase, to do a chase.

00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:12.230
And the Earth guy,
because he hasn't quite

00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:19.660
acclimated to Ceres, he runs
so hard that he goes up.

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:24.112
Because he's much stronger, he's
does a Superman kind of a jump.

00:22:24.112 --> 00:22:26.070
And we wrote it into the
script a couple times,

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:28.140
and the director was
just going, guys, it's

00:22:28.140 --> 00:22:29.846
going to look stupid.

00:22:29.846 --> 00:22:31.530
MARK FERGUS: That's the thing.

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:35.190
If it doesn't feel
like part of the show,

00:22:35.190 --> 00:22:37.010
it will just look like
the guy's an idiot.

00:22:37.010 --> 00:22:39.930
And the bike trick looked like
a stupid bike trick on Earth,

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:40.430
really.

00:22:40.430 --> 00:22:41.630
NAREN SHANKAR: In that
case, we were idiots.

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:43.162
MARK FERGUS: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:22:43.162 --> 00:22:45.360
But the bird, you see
the wings flapping

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:48.830
a third of the amount of time,
and the bird hovering aloft.

00:22:48.830 --> 00:22:51.700
It's one way, and Coriolis.

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:53.550
There's a few things
that actually landed,

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:55.850
and hopefully we
paint enough points

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:58.110
that you realize the
whole environment.

00:22:58.110 --> 00:23:00.320
But use ones that are
visual and distinctive.

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:02.407
NAREN SHANKAR: One that
worked really well,

