where Miller's
manipulating a star map,

00:33:56.750 --> 00:33:58.660
and it's really gorgeous.

00:33:58.660 --> 00:34:01.050
Thomas Jane did
whatever he wanted to.

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:05.040
He was doing deliberate
things, but then our animators

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:07.170
animated to it.

00:34:07.170 --> 00:34:08.420
And nothing was choreographed.

00:34:08.420 --> 00:34:10.389
He simply just did
what he felt was right.

00:34:10.389 --> 00:34:12.170
He understood the
moments in the script,

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:14.190
because they were scripted.

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:17.614
But the actual visual effect was
created to match his movement,

00:34:17.614 --> 00:34:19.030
and that's why it
feels very real.

00:34:22.497 --> 00:34:23.330
AUDIENCE: Hey, guys.

00:34:23.330 --> 00:34:24.590
Thanks a lot for
coming out today.

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:25.510
Naren, if it makes
you feel any better,

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:27.010
I didn't have a
briefcase, but I had

00:34:27.010 --> 00:34:28.380
one of those rolling backpacks.

00:34:28.380 --> 00:34:29.645
NAREN SHANKAR: Right, you
know what I'm talking about.

00:34:29.645 --> 00:34:31.900
AUDIENCE: I used to get
the crap beat out of me.

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:35.639
NAREN SHANKAR: See, I'm a little
older, so I didn't have that.

00:34:35.639 --> 00:34:37.100
MARK FERGUS: Technology.

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:40.002
NAREN SHANKAR: No, no wheels
then, not for the children.

00:34:40.002 --> 00:34:42.210
AUDIENCE: Guys, I have a
question more on the writing

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:43.670
side.

00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:46.969
I'm curious to hear from
you how much actors had

00:34:46.969 --> 00:34:49.239
an influence on the writings.

00:34:49.239 --> 00:34:51.500
NAREN SHANKAR: As
little as possible.

00:34:51.500 --> 00:34:54.066
AUDIENCE: One can hope.

00:34:54.066 --> 00:34:55.940
But I mean, obviously
there's a character arc

00:34:55.940 --> 00:34:58.880
you have to follow, a story
arc for every character,

00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:01.790
and the books give you
guidance, but after seeing

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:04.060
what the actors could
do, how much did that

00:35:04.060 --> 00:35:07.820
influence your writing,
based on their own qualities

00:35:07.820 --> 00:35:08.710
and limitations?

00:35:08.710 --> 00:35:11.800
MARK FERGUS: I mean, certainly
once the actors start

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:14.230
to own the character, and you
get tuned to their rhythm,

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:17.610
and you see the way they're
burrowing in, what they resist,

00:35:17.610 --> 00:35:21.470
what really unlocks
their inner greatness,

00:35:21.470 --> 00:35:24.470
you start to see
what works for them.

00:35:24.470 --> 00:35:28.560
Thomas Jane, for example,
he's a very emotional actor,

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:30.580
but he plays it
with the emotions

00:35:30.580 --> 00:35:31.850
bubbling under the surface.

00:35:31.850 --> 00:35:33.620
If you give him an
opportunity for that,

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:35.720
he sinks his teeth into a scene.

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:38.010
If you want him to
play overtly emotional,

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:42.050
and weepy, and over-the-top,
that shuts him down,

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:45.840
because it doesn't really
tap into what he's great at.

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:49.200
So it's our job not to
change the story based

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:52.270
on everybody's ideas,
because then you have chaos,

00:35:52.270 --> 00:35:55.830
but to listen to what's
working, to really

00:35:55.830 --> 00:35:58.700
start shaping it for that
actor, and then listening.

00:35:58.700 --> 00:36:00.900
They start to have
ownership over these people,

00:36:00.900 --> 00:36:02.170
and they start saying,
hey, you know what?

00:36:02.170 --> 00:36:04.503
I'm a little uncomfortable
with this moment or whatever.

00:36:04.503 --> 00:36:06.150
And then make them
feel safe to be

00:36:06.150 --> 00:36:08.660
able to bring their
thoughts and ideas

00:36:08.660 --> 00:36:10.600
and keep it open like that.

00:36:10.600 --> 00:36:12.205
So it ended up
working both ways,

00:36:12.205 --> 00:36:16.766
but we try to really
commit to story choices.

00:36:16.766 --> 00:36:19.793
But then the texture
of it, the way into it

00:36:19.793 --> 00:36:25.272
align, I think we've been really
happy the more it engages them,

00:36:25.272 --> 00:36:26.730
the more we want
to hear from them.

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:28.940
And it's been a really
great relationship.

00:36:28.940 --> 00:36:32.030
NAREN SHANKAR: We
also, in our process,

00:36:32.030 --> 00:36:35.630
the way we develop the season,
we have a lot of material

00:36:35.630 --> 00:36:38.400
at the script stage
going into a season.

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:41.960
And so the actors get big
chunks of material at a time,

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:44.680
and when they are
able to read it,

00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:48.080
when they see it stretched out
over a story arc or a character

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:50.946
arc over several
episodes, I think

00:36:50.946 --> 00:36:52.320
it gives them a
lot of confidence

00:36:52.320 --> 00:36:54.400
that the people who are
writing the material

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:56.270
know where they're going.

00:36:56.270 --> 00:36:58.370
And actors get
concerned when they

00:36:58.370 --> 00:37:00.120
feel like things are
happening at random

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:04.300
or for no reason, or
capriciously, or arbitrarily.

00:37:04.300 --> 00:37:05.680
That's when they get weird.

00:37:05.680 --> 00:37:08.004
But when they see that the
story is actually happening,

00:37:08.004 --> 00:37:09.920
and there's meaning
behind what they're doing,

00:37:09.920 --> 00:37:11.003
then they get comfortable.

00:37:11.003 --> 00:37:13.460
And that's been our experience.

00:37:13.460 --> 00:37:16.000
They will chime in.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:17.635
Things get shaded a
little differently.

00:37:17.635 --> 00:37:19.260
There's an interpretation
that maybe we

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:22.510
didn't see that we're
certainly happy to dig into.

00:37:22.510 --> 00:37:25.020
But by and large, they've
stayed on the page.

00:37:25.020 --> 00:37:25.770
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:37:25.770 --> 00:37:26.310
Thanks guys.

00:37:29.860 --> 00:37:32.070
AUDIENCE: So I really
enjoyed the first season,

00:37:32.070 --> 00:37:33.700
and I got a ton of
questions, but I

00:37:33.700 --> 00:37:37.010
think I narrowed it to two.

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:40.087
One of them is about whole
treatment of sound in space.

00:37:40.087 --> 00:37:41.920
I'm just curious how
you guys feel about it,

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:45.670
because right now, we're
seeing a lot of people

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:48.730
going for the soundless effect.

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:51.867
And I appreciate both
versions in the right context,

00:37:51.867 --> 00:37:53.450
but I was just wonder
whether you guys

00:37:53.450 --> 00:37:54.594
had thoughts about that.

00:37:54.594 --> 00:37:56.260
NAREN SHANKAR: I
should tell this story.

00:37:59.650 --> 00:38:00.780
We talked about that.

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:02.452
MARK FERGUS: Let's
put it this way.

00:38:02.452 --> 00:38:06.318
This has been a very
important decision

00:38:06.318 --> 00:38:08.469
and an important discussion,
so it was not made--

00:38:08.469 --> 00:38:10.260
NAREN SHANKAR: No, it
was not made lightly.

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:14.570
A couple of things.

00:38:14.570 --> 00:38:17.320
Every show has done things
a little bit differently.

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:21.460
"Galactica," for example,
they took a muffled soundscape

00:38:21.460 --> 00:38:23.190
in space, and so
they crunched things

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:24.380
down a little bit sonically.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:26.360
It was interesting.

00:38:26.360 --> 00:38:29.890
When we started developing
the sound design for the show,

00:38:29.890 --> 00:38:31.860
we had some guys who
were like, we really

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.510
want to use these
contact mics on things,

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:36.260
and they were hitting
things, because they

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:38.500
wanted it to sound like the
astronauts in their suits

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:40.370
on the ISS.

00:38:40.370 --> 00:38:42.690
Oh, isn't that going to be
really neat and everything?

00:38:42.690 --> 00:38:44.580
And so they did
all of this work,

00:38:44.580 --> 00:38:47.810
and they put these
sounds in the show.

00:38:47.810 --> 00:38:51.440
And we're watching it,
and we go that sucks.

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:54.650
It's like you have people
walking down a creepy corridor,

00:38:54.650 --> 00:38:57.980
and you're hearing something
that goes dun, dun, dun.

00:38:57.980 --> 00:39:00.200
It just sounds like they're
stepping on plastic.

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.230
And so there's no tension.

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:03.040
There was no scare.

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:05.730
And so even though
that was the real sound

00:39:05.730 --> 00:39:07.230
of what was happening
and probably

00:39:07.230 --> 00:39:09.900
what would be conducted
through your spacesuit

00:39:09.900 --> 00:39:13.700
when you're hitting something
in a vacuum, it didn't matter.

00:39:13.700 --> 00:39:15.230
What it was doing
was dramatically

00:39:15.230 --> 00:39:18.390
it was ruining the
goddamn moment.

00:39:18.390 --> 00:39:23.880
And so what happened
was we made the decision

00:39:23.880 --> 00:39:30.150
to go big, to go gut wrenching,
and things that are moving fast

00:39:30.150 --> 00:39:31.900
and have a tremendous
amount of mass,

00:39:31.900 --> 00:39:35.510
make them feel big and
heavy, and fast and scary.

00:39:35.510 --> 00:39:37.180
It's an aesthetic choice.

00:39:37.180 --> 00:39:38.800
I mean, we would
sit in the mixes,

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:40.580
and I'd be going scare
the shit out of me!

00:39:40.580 --> 00:39:43.750
It's like, turn the thing up.

00:39:43.750 --> 00:39:45.910
And it's half of
what you perceive

00:39:45.910 --> 00:39:48.370
as entertainment is sound.

00:39:48.370 --> 00:39:52.350
it's an incredibly, incredibly
important element to it.

00:39:52.350 --> 00:39:56.080
And they've done tests
where they'll show audiences

00:39:56.080 --> 00:39:58.200
the exact same film.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:02.010
And one version is a crappy
mix, and the second version

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:03.410
is an amazing mix.

00:40:03.410 --> 00:40:05.430
And the perception
from the audience

00:40:05.430 --> 00:40:07.870
is that the one with a good
mix has a better picture.

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:12.270
It's an amazing thing.

00:40:12.270 --> 00:40:13.850
It's just how we
perceive the world.

00:40:13.850 --> 00:40:17.900
So the story I like to
tell is that years ago, I

00:40:17.900 --> 00:40:20.280
was doing a show called
"The Outer Limits,"

00:40:20.280 --> 00:40:23.420
and it was an anthology
science fiction show.

00:40:23.420 --> 00:40:24.856
And we were filming in a cave.

00:40:24.856 --> 00:40:26.730
I mean, it was like we
were doing a cave set,

00:40:26.730 --> 00:40:27.490
and there's lights.

00:40:27.490 --> 00:40:28.610
And I was going, oh my god.

00:40:28.610 --> 00:40:29.420
What are these
lights coming from?

00:40:29.420 --> 00:40:30.128
It's in the cave.

00:40:30.128 --> 00:40:30.930
This is dark.

00:40:30.930 --> 00:40:33.830
And the DP on the show
told me this story

00:40:33.830 --> 00:40:37.450
about an old movie, the
'50s, James Mason, "Journey

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:38.670
to the Center of the Earth."

00:40:38.670 --> 00:40:41.554
The director had a breakdown
during the filming,

00:40:41.554 --> 00:40:43.220
because he suddenly
realized, oh my god.

00:40:43.220 --> 00:40:44.050
We're inside the Earth.

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:45.341
Where is the light coming from?

00:40:45.341 --> 00:40:46.700
And he's freaking out.

00:40:46.700 --> 00:40:49.450
And the DP goes, it's
coming from the same place

00:40:49.450 --> 00:40:51.012
as the music.

00:40:51.012 --> 00:40:53.417
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:57.265 --> 00:40:58.590
MARK FERGUS: Absolutely.

00:40:58.590 --> 00:40:59.423
AUDIENCE: I like it.

00:40:59.423 --> 00:40:59.923
Cool.

00:41:03.390 --> 00:41:06.460
MARK FERGUS: Sound, I
think sound is the language

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:08.485
of the subconscious, the heart.

00:41:08.485 --> 00:41:11.710
It is so much more primal than
visual and any other element

00:41:11.710 --> 00:41:12.892
that we've got going.

00:41:12.892 --> 00:41:16.580
And to leave that off the
palette to tell your story,

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:19.330
it's just not realistic,
and it's one of those things

00:41:19.330 --> 00:41:21.630
you have to let go, because
we're telling a story here,

00:41:21.630 --> 00:41:25.200
and we're taking so
many of our colors away.

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:28.400
And the subconscious stuff
that makes you see differently

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:31.130
because you're hearing
differently, to lose that

00:41:31.130 --> 00:41:33.952
is hobbling everything
we're trying to do.

00:41:33.952 --> 00:41:35.410
So you've just got
to say screw it.

00:41:38.030 --> 00:41:42.680
NICK FARMER: And just to insert
a comment on that, certainly

00:41:42.680 --> 00:41:44.930
with the language
part, there's nothing

00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:47.770
so viscerally foreign
as hearing a language

00:41:47.770 --> 00:41:49.430
that you don't understand.

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:53.700
And that's because there's
just some parts of your brain

00:41:53.700 --> 00:41:55.490
that are so keyed into that.

00:41:55.490 --> 00:41:59.280
MARK FERGUS: It's why
music can wreck you.

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:01.120
A great song or a song
that brings you back

00:42:01.120 --> 00:42:03.050
to your childhood,
or a song that

00:42:03.050 --> 00:42:05.799
hits the right-- it
holds, and then it lets

00:42:05.799 --> 00:42:07.590
go, and you feel like
you're going to weep.

00:42:07.590 --> 00:42:08.920
No one can figure that out.

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:11.530
NAREN SHANKAR: It's the lizard
part of your brain, honestly.

00:42:11.530 --> 00:42:15.150
MARK FERGUS: You've got
to grab every bit of that.

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:16.870
And in a box that
we have 42 minutes

00:42:16.870 --> 00:42:21.460
to tell a story with
all these elements,

00:42:21.460 --> 00:42:25.920
sound is so, so important.

00:42:25.920 --> 00:42:28.650
I appreciate the question,
because it's one of those ones

00:42:28.650 --> 00:42:32.180
that we really did not--
we're a science-based show.

00:42:32.180 --> 00:42:33.005
We tried--

00:42:33.005 --> 00:42:34.380
NAREN SHANKAR: We
really did try.

00:42:34.380 --> 00:42:36.040
AUDIENCE: You guys got
a lot of good details.

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:37.046
MARK FERGUS: That one, screw it.

00:42:37.046 --> 00:42:38.379
NAREN SHANKAR: It sucked so bad.

00:42:38.379 --> 00:42:41.390
It was so bad.

00:42:41.390 --> 00:42:43.460
AUDIENCE: I liked
it, though, thanks.

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:46.600
The second question
is, between how

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:49.380
you have a book series going
on and you have a television

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:51.430
series, you've got these
two separate things.

00:42:54.630 --> 00:42:57.390
And book, television often
will take some liberties

00:42:57.390 --> 00:42:59.410
from the books, but
is there any moment

00:42:59.410 --> 00:43:01.707
where you feel like, I just
want to take the lead now.

00:43:01.707 --> 00:43:03.040
Do you ever think it catches up?

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.500
Kind of like the
Marvel universe,

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:09.942
how the movies are now
influencing the comics more.

00:43:09.942 --> 00:43:11.900
I know the authors may
have rights to all this,

00:43:11.900 --> 00:43:13.970
but do you ever think,
I got an idea for this,

00:43:13.970 --> 00:43:16.894
how it should go?

00:43:16.894 --> 00:43:18.060
NAREN SHANKAR: I don't know.

00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:20.170
I think that the problem
is when you take it out

00:43:20.170 --> 00:43:24.320
of the imagination and
you put it on the film,

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:26.520
you're stuck with those faces.

00:43:26.520 --> 00:43:27.920
You're stuck with that world.

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:30.760
And I mean, that's really a
question for Ty and Daniel,

00:43:30.760 --> 00:43:33.279
because they're the ones
who are writing the books.

00:43:33.279 --> 00:43:35.570
MARK FERGUS: We're not going
to catch up any time soon.

00:43:35.570 --> 00:43:37.528
NAREN SHANKAR: No, we're
not going to catch up,

00:43:37.528 --> 00:43:40.450
but it's an
interesting question.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:42.710
You need to send it to them.

00:43:42.710 --> 00:43:46.610
Are they being influenced on
the writing side novelistically

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:49.710
by what they're seeing
in the television show?

00:43:49.710 --> 00:43:51.340
And I don't know
what the answer is.

00:43:51.340 --> 00:43:53.040
Because we're
following their lead,

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:55.044
and we're trying not
to change too much.

00:43:55.044 --> 00:43:56.460
We're trying to
stay real faithful

00:43:56.460 --> 00:44:00.310
and make it a real,
true adaptation of what

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:02.910
they've written.

00:44:02.910 --> 00:44:06.040
But I think it may be inevitable
to have some cross talk.

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:10.660
MARK FERGUS: I wonder if just
the visuals of the actors

00:44:10.660 --> 00:44:14.470
we've chosen who really
own-- Naomi Nagata was very

00:44:14.470 --> 00:44:16.110
specifically
described in the book,

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:20.350
and our actress Dominique played
exactly what's on the page,

00:44:20.350 --> 00:44:25.720
except she put all the pain
inside, instead of wearing it

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:28.080
on her sleeve, and the
character in the book more

00:44:28.080 --> 00:44:29.980
wore her-- she would shut down.

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:32.010
She would hide, and
Dominique doesn't do that.

00:44:32.010 --> 00:44:38.774
But you can tell there's a ton
of pain and anxiety, and joy,

00:44:38.774 --> 00:44:40.440
and everything else
going on underneath,

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:42.660
but she lets it out in
a tough kind of way.

00:44:42.660 --> 00:44:45.450
And I don't know
how you can not get

00:44:45.450 --> 00:44:49.540
infected with her version of the
character writing her forward.

00:44:49.540 --> 00:44:53.810
I don't know if those
guys get tainted by that,

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:55.450
or were affected by that.

00:44:55.450 --> 00:44:59.200
But we'll certainly have
to read the new books

00:44:59.200 --> 00:45:01.327
and see if we're
having any effect.

00:45:01.327 --> 00:45:01.952
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:45:01.952 --> 00:45:02.800
Thank you.

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:05.730
NICK FARMER: So we have time
for one last quick question.

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:07.480
AUDIENCE: It's pretty
quick, but thank you

00:45:07.480 --> 00:45:08.827
for coming, first of all.

00:45:08.827 --> 00:45:10.050
MARK FERGUS: Thank you.

00:45:10.050 --> 00:45:15.010
AUDIENCE: When I saw your pilot,
the sci-fi geek side of me

00:45:15.010 --> 00:45:18.300
said what technological
advancement happened

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:20.310
in the history of
the show that allowed

00:45:20.310 --> 00:45:24.940
so many people and so much
material to get up into orbit?

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:27.137
Did you guys talk about that?

00:45:27.137 --> 00:45:28.470
NAREN SHANKAR: Yeah, absolutely.

00:45:28.470 --> 00:45:28.970
AUDIENCE: How do
you explain that?

00:45:28.970 --> 00:45:30.080
What was your idea on that?

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:31.413
NAREN SHANKAR: It's not my idea.

00:45:31.413 --> 00:45:33.520
It's Ty and Daniel's idea.

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:34.660
It's a fusion drive.

00:45:34.660 --> 00:45:36.450
It's an efficient
fusion drive that

00:45:36.450 --> 00:45:39.380
allows colonization
of the solar system,

00:45:39.380 --> 00:45:40.970
and really compresses
the time it

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:45.900
takes to get to Mars, the
Belt, and to the planets.

00:45:45.900 --> 00:45:47.765
That's really it.

00:45:47.765 --> 00:45:50.270
And everything stems from it.

00:45:50.270 --> 00:45:52.870
And they wrote a
lovely novella called

00:45:52.870 --> 00:45:57.160
"Drive," about the
discovery of what's

00:45:57.160 --> 00:45:58.210
called the Epstein Drive.

00:45:58.210 --> 00:46:00.510
It's Solomon Epstein,
the guy who finds it.

00:46:00.510 --> 00:46:04.740
And we're actually finding a
way to incorporate that story

00:46:04.740 --> 00:46:07.910
into season 2, so
you'll actually

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:09.200
get a nice little explanation.

00:46:09.200 --> 00:46:11.230
AUDIENCE: That would be very
satisfying, intellectually.

00:46:11.230 --> 00:46:12.896
NAREN SHANKAR: I think
it will actually.

00:46:12.896 --> 00:46:16.202
Because it's really is one of
my favorites of the novellas.

00:46:16.202 --> 00:46:17.452
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:46:17.452 --> 00:46:19.060
NAREN SHANKAR: Sure.

00:46:19.060 --> 00:46:20.710
NICK FARMER: Very, very last.

00:46:20.710 --> 00:46:22.780
AUDIENCE: Well, thank
you very much for coming.

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:27.910
I love your story about coming
from a science background.

00:46:27.910 --> 00:46:32.390
But my question is that when
you have such an enormous power

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:36.580
to reach the public by
your writing and putting it

00:46:36.580 --> 00:46:41.250
on a TV series, with a
subject that is futuristic,

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:45.465
and of course involves a lot
of technology and science,

00:46:45.465 --> 00:46:49.060
and given that this is
a hot topic these days,

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:54.950
the scientific communities,
whether film and TV series can

00:46:54.950 --> 00:47:01.060
be a tool for enhancing public
understanding of science

00:47:01.060 --> 00:47:03.750
and so on, for this
particular show,

00:47:03.750 --> 00:47:09.806
have you come across the debate
whether we should have science

00:47:09.806 --> 00:47:12.190
advisors on the team
or, or whether this

00:47:12.190 --> 00:47:18.200
is a good place for enhancing
public understanding

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:19.800
of science,

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:23.430
how would that affect our
ratings or the type of audience

00:47:23.430 --> 00:47:25.230
in terms of demographics?

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:30.030
And I haven't watched the show,
but understand that technology

00:47:30.030 --> 00:47:31.510
is in the background,
and it's not

00:47:31.510 --> 00:47:34.090
the main purpose of
the show, but have

00:47:34.090 --> 00:47:36.154
you have you had
any talks about it,

00:47:36.154 --> 00:47:37.570
or discussion about
how would that

00:47:37.570 --> 00:47:41.170
affect the ratings,
or the audience,

00:47:41.170 --> 00:47:43.086
and possibly the
collaboration with

00:47:43.086 --> 00:47:44.210
the scientific communities.

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:45.668
MARK FERGUS: I
think audiences have

00:47:45.668 --> 00:47:47.900
loved the-- when I say
tech in the background,

00:47:47.900 --> 00:47:51.710
I mean the idea that we'd
be focusing on robotics

00:47:51.710 --> 00:47:52.360
or whatever.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:54.151
But what people have
been really responding

00:47:54.151 --> 00:47:57.810
to is the science of what
happens to the human body

00:47:57.810 --> 00:47:59.990
when you go really
fast across space?

00:47:59.990 --> 00:48:01.830
You have the ability to do it.

00:48:01.830 --> 00:48:04.120
The only problem is the human
body can't withstand it,

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:09.860
so you have to go through
a very painful drug regimen

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:14.470
to convince your body not to
die while you're going 20 Gs.

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:16.510
And then the ship
will flip halfway

00:48:16.510 --> 00:48:18.270
through the journey
and start burning

00:48:18.270 --> 00:48:19.570
in the opposite direction.

00:48:19.570 --> 00:48:22.380
It will break for half
the journey as it sped up.

00:48:22.380 --> 00:48:25.840
People are loving the
mechanics of travel,

00:48:25.840 --> 00:48:30.180
that we're showing how
this might feasibly

00:48:30.180 --> 00:48:33.400
get a ship of massive
mass and density

00:48:33.400 --> 00:48:35.060
across a huge ocean of space.

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:37.000
And we're showing
you how it gets done,

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:40.740
and we're showing how
gravity, when thrust stops,

00:48:40.740 --> 00:48:42.564
or directionality.

00:48:42.564 --> 00:48:43.980
People are standing
in the ceiling

00:48:43.980 --> 00:48:45.810
if their engines
over here, and we're

00:48:45.810 --> 00:48:48.970
showing how directionality
in sci-fi is all wrong,

00:48:48.970 --> 00:48:52.140
and when you stop thrust or
acceleration, you lose gravity.

00:48:52.140 --> 00:48:54.680
All that stuff, people are
digging that about the show.

00:48:54.680 --> 00:48:58.470
So I think it's we're seeing
tons of reaction in the public

00:48:58.470 --> 00:49:00.360
to how cool is that.

00:49:00.360 --> 00:49:03.110
So we feel like it's really
distinguishing the show rather

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:04.940
than becoming a
hindrance in any way.

00:49:04.940 --> 00:49:07.890
NAREN SHANKAR: You
know what it is?

00:49:07.890 --> 00:49:10.700
With these novels,
Ty and Daniel,

00:49:10.700 --> 00:49:15.320
they really did a tremendous
amount of research,

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:18.570
and they put a lot of science
into the books already.

00:49:18.570 --> 00:49:22.250
And so what was great
about it was they

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:25.650
found ways to express that
science in dramatically

00:49:25.650 --> 00:49:27.680
interesting ways.

00:49:27.680 --> 00:49:30.200
And so that's what
we're doing in the show.

00:49:30.200 --> 00:49:32.299
So we don't have a
science advisor around,

00:49:32.299 --> 00:49:34.090
because generally we
don't really need one.

00:49:34.090 --> 00:49:36.590
I mean, I had science advisors
and technical advisors

00:49:36.590 --> 00:49:39.440
on "CSI," but that
was a forensic show,

00:49:39.440 --> 00:49:42.010
and that was incredibly
important for that.

00:49:42.010 --> 00:49:46.020
But here, the situations and
the problems that come up

00:49:46.020 --> 00:49:47.720
are already well
thought through.

00:49:47.720 --> 00:49:52.010
We did an episode where we have
two of our characters running

00:49:52.010 --> 00:49:56.290
across a catwalk towards
to try to escape,

00:49:56.290 --> 00:50:00.030
and in the middle of their
run, the ship's main thrust,

00:50:00.030 --> 00:50:02.510
main engine goes out,
and so they lose gravity.

00:50:02.510 --> 00:50:04.190
And as they're
running, their momentum

00:50:04.190 --> 00:50:06.170
carries them up into the air.

00:50:06.170 --> 00:50:08.410
And the only way
they can get back

00:50:08.410 --> 00:50:12.200
is one of the guys clips a
tether onto the other person,

00:50:12.200 --> 00:50:15.410
flips around as they're
floating up, pushes her up,

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:19.340
which pushes him down, slams
him back on the catwalk.

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:22.630
He attaches to it, and then
that allows him to come back.

00:50:22.630 --> 00:50:26.740
It's a beautiful illustration
of the third law,

00:50:26.740 --> 00:50:28.670
but we don't say we're
going to teach you

00:50:28.670 --> 00:50:34.020
about action and reaction,
but it's really interesting.

00:50:34.020 --> 00:50:36.790
But that's how we're
doing science in the show.

00:50:36.790 --> 00:50:40.080
There's another sequence in that
same episode, actually, where

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:44.300
our people are in a compartment,
and the gravity goes out again.

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:45.330
Thrust goes out.

00:50:45.330 --> 00:50:48.960
And a rail gunshot comes through
the cabin instantaneously,

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:52.400
and basically
vaporizes a guy's head.

00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:55.260
And so the air rushes
out of the cabin.

00:50:55.260 --> 00:50:57.660
The guy's still bleeding
in zero gravity,

00:50:57.660 --> 00:51:00.450
so the blood forms
this little blood head

00:51:00.450 --> 00:51:03.650
over where his real head was.

00:51:03.650 --> 00:51:06.460
They finally seal
the compartment

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:08.670
in zero G. The
gravity comes back on,

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:13.710
and then the blood head goes--
just splashes on the ground.

00:51:13.710 --> 00:51:16.197
One website did a
whole calculation.

00:51:16.197 --> 00:51:18.780
They did a mass flow calculation
on the whole thing, and said,

00:51:18.780 --> 00:51:19.946
well we got it pretty right.

00:51:19.946 --> 00:51:21.020
We were off by about 20%.

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:21.603
It's like, OK.

00:51:21.603 --> 00:51:24.190
20% drama means 100% right.

00:51:28.530 --> 00:51:29.990
But that's the fun
of the show, is

00:51:29.990 --> 00:51:34.790
that you're showing science in
a dramatic way without really--

00:51:34.790 --> 00:51:36.630
we're not teaching.

00:51:36.630 --> 00:51:37.510
It's not school.

00:51:37.510 --> 00:51:39.720
It's not a textbook.

00:51:39.720 --> 00:51:41.870
What people are really
responding to, as Mark said,

00:51:41.870 --> 00:51:45.010
is that they understand
it, because it feels real.

00:51:45.010 --> 00:51:46.620
And they're seeing
something that

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:49.470
is being portrayed in a way
they really haven't before.

00:51:49.470 --> 00:51:51.820
And I think in that
respect, it's really nice

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:53.330
to be able to do
that in the show,

00:51:53.330 --> 00:51:56.730
because you're
expressing science.

00:51:56.730 --> 00:52:01.990
You may not be teaching it, but
you're being faithful to it.

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:02.990
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:02.990 --> 00:52:05.560
NICK FARMER: Well, thank you
guys for coming and giving us

00:52:05.560 --> 00:52:07.254
this wonderful discussion.

00:52:07.254 --> 00:52:08.420
NAREN SHANKAR: Our pleasure.

00:52:08.420 --> 00:52:09.378
MARK FERGUS: Thank you.

00:52:09.378 --> 00:52:12.070
[APPLAUSE]

